Year In Review: A Travel Writer's 10 Best Hotel Stays Of 2025 - Forbes
  URL: https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/2026/01/06/year-in-review-a-travel-writers-10-best-hotel-stays-of-2025/
  This year, luxury hotels evolved from traditional, old-school opulence toward experience-driven, personalized stays.

  --- Content ---
  [Lifestyle](https://www.forbes.com/lifestyle/)[Travel](https://www.forbes.com/travel/)
  
  # Year In Review: A Travel Writer’s 10 Best Hotel Stays Of 2025
  
  Reviews of the best hotel stays from a year spent traveling, including when to go and why.
  
  By [Jennifer Leigh Parker](https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/ "https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/"),
  
  Contributor.
  
  Forbes contributors publish independent expert analyses and insights.
  Covering the future of luxury travel.
  
  Follow Author
  
  Jan 06, 2026, 04:51pm ESTUpdated Jan 8, 2026, 03:16pm EST
  
  0
  
  ![Hôtel de Crillon, A Rosewood Hotel in Paris, France](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7d109895694e7f5aafb1/H-tel-de-Crillon--A-Rosewood-Hotel-in-Paris--France/1960x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=1440)
  
  Hôtel de Crillon, A Rosewood Hotel in Paris, France
  
  Courtesy Hôtel de Crillon, A Rosewood Hotel
  
  This year, luxury hotels evolved from traditional, old-school opulence toward experience-driven, personalized stays. It’s been happening for a few years now, but this year the trend reached new, sometimes preposterous levels.
  
  The reason why is simple: There are more millionaires and billionaires in the world now than at any point in history, and if they’re not pleased with hotel service, they can easily opt for fully staffed private villas or yachts instead. Which is why hoteliers are falling all over themselves to become more attractive to the biggest spenders. The rest of us get to ride the ripples of the waves.
  
  Gone are the days where a stay is just a stay. A stay is an experience to write home about. The best hotels open formerly locked doors and reflect what a particular destination has to offer in a microcosm.With that in mind, here are the top 10 hotels I visited in 2025, in chronological order. From hiking the Atlas Mountains in Morocco to surfing the waves in Costa Rica and the rooftop bars of London, these particular hotels helped stage unforgettable moments.
  
  _Author’s note: January is for reflection and resets. This year-in-review thus begins in the snowy and romantic month of February, 2025. It should also be noted that this list does not include wellness resort-clinic hybrids. My forthcoming “longevity list” is another story altogether._
  
  ![The Surrey, A Corinthia Hotel in New York ](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7da42df5e5dbc639502b/The-Surrey--A-Corinthia-Hotel-in-New-York/1960x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  The Grand Deluxe Suite inside The Surrey, A Corinthia Hotel
  
  Courtesy Corinthia Hotels
  
  **1) February \| The Surrey, A Corinthia Hotel, New York**
  
  The fate of the Surrey, which reopened its doors on 76th street on the corner of Madison Avenue as a Corinthia Hotel in September 2024, was all but certain. But a few months in, the dishy debut of [Casa Tua](https://www.corinthia.com/en-gb/new-york/restaurants-bars/ "https://www.corinthia.com/en-gb/new-york/restaurants-bars/") as its main restaurant and private membership club, along with the jewel-box [Surrey Spa](https://www.corinthia.com/en-gb/new-york/wellness/ "https://www.corinthia.com/en-gb/new-york/wellness/"), with its plumping black rose facials and salt tepidarium, garnered a great deal of buzz during the broad cultural revival of the Upper East Side — to which a booth at Casa Tua is now considered a front row seat. Move over old money, the _nouvelle vague’s_ in town, and they’re taking your tables. (Share Casa Tua’s pistachio gelato with someone special, and it might change your life).
  
  “We partnered in New York with Casa Tua to bring immediate life and relevance. Because a hotel is really brought to life by the foot traffic, by the people that come. You want to be relevant to the community,” Simon Casson, Chief Executive Officer of Corinthia Hotels told me over coffee in the elegant lounge designed by Martin Brudnizki Design Studio and populated by cosmopolitans who absolutely don’t need anti-aging treatments, but they’re getting them anyway. After 35 years with Four Seasons Hotels, Casson is a hospitality veteran and fitness fanatic with so much panache the world simply didn’t allow him to retire. Corinthia managed to appeal to Casson’s competitive drive, and now he’s the brand’s secret weapon CEO with a mandate to “grow Corinthia into a global luxury brand.” In 2026 and beyond, he’ll certainly be one to watch.
  
  **Why Book?** Across the street, the Carlyle — Grand Dame of the Upper East Side — is too often overrun with tourists. The Surrey is an attractive alternative.
  
  ![Cocktails at the hotel’s new speakeasy, The Bar. ](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7e4c9fe8eaca1382d232/Cocktails-at-the-hotel-s-new-speakeasy--The-Bar-/1960x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Cocktails at the hotel’s new speakeasy, The Bar.
  
  Courtesy Mandarin Oriental New York
  
  **2) February \| Mandarin Oriental, New York**
  
  If you really want to know how the other half lives, check out [Suite 5000](https://www.mandarinoriental.com/en/new-york/manhattan/stay/suite-5000 "https://www.mandarinoriental.com/en/new-york/manhattan/stay/suite-5000") on the 50th floor of the Mandarin Oriental hotel overlooking Central Park. Press a button and watch the curtains rise from floor-to-ceiling windows in this 3,300 square feet expanse with two bedrooms and 2.5 baths, and you can faintly detect the curvature of the earth — along with Columbus Circle, the entire south side of the park, and all the twinkling lights below. _This_, you’ll think, is what Frank Sinatra got all worked up about.
  
  But that’s not the real reason Mandarin won my heart. The real reason can be boiled down to one evening spent catching up with Director of Communications Gail Cowper, to celebrate the hotel’s new speakeasy, [The Bar](https://www.mandarinoriental.com/en/new-york/manhattan/dine/the-bar "https://www.mandarinoriental.com/en/new-york/manhattan/dine/the-bar"). Firstly, she never misses a chance to ask: _How are you?_ And secondly, its cowhide and leather barstools, vintage globes and Silk Road-themed cocktails are aimed squarely at the hearts of self-professed world travelers who wear rumpled safari jackets in urban settings (me) and own an embarrassing amount of quills with ink pots (also me). Even in dry January, a rendez-vous here is a good idea.
  
  **Why Book?** The Mandarin used to be a cold distant high-rise in the sky. Now, the new speakeasy scene and culinary staff are turning the hotel into a warm, welcoming hearth in winter — where everyone knows your name.
  
  ![Kasbah Tamadot's reflecting pool at night](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7ea517d963f411a92f99/Kasbah-Tamadot-s-reflecting-pool-at-night/1960x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Kasbah Tamadot's reflecting pool at night
  
  Courtesy Virgin Limited Edition Hotels
  
  **3) March \| Richard Branson’s Kasbah Tamadot, Morocco**
  
  Richard Branson’s resplendent resort outside Marrakech is steeped in the kind of exoticism that only comes from a deep understanding of a place and a long-term commitment to its people. [Kasbah Tamadot](https://www.virginlimitededition.com/kasbah-tamadot/ "https://www.virginlimitededition.com/kasbah-tamadot/") first opened as a Virgin Limited Edition property in 2005, and was fully restored following the 6.8 magnitude earthquake that struck Morocco’s Al Haouz region in 2023. Now, what you experience as a hotel guest is the result of Branson’s trademark determination to build-back-better. If you’re of a strong constitution, take one of the hotel’s guided hikes into the High Atlas mountains and visit the Berber villagers who survived the earthquake. Being served Moroccan mint tea inside a real Berber tent, where families live without plumbing or heat in the desert chill is a deeply humbling experience. Their resilience is not something you soon forget. “If you care passionately enough, I believe you can improve on any facet of the human experience,” Sir Richard Branson said of this place, which he spent millions rebuilding. (Read the full backstory [here](https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/2025/04/30/rock-the-kasbah-inside-richard-bransons-moroccan-dream-resort/ "https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/2025/04/30/rock-the-kasbah-inside-richard-bransons-moroccan-dream-resort/")).
  
  **Why Book?** Booking the Kasbah directly supports the local Moroccans employed by the resort. For many of them, the Kasbah is a lifeline.
  
  ![The pool deck at Nekajui, Ritz Carlton, in Costa Rica](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7f41992273ad9c980089/The-pool-deck-at-Nekajui--Ritz-Carlton--in-Costa-Rica/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  The pool deck at Nekajui, Ritz Carlton, in Costa Rica
  
  Courtesy Ritz Carlton
  
  **4) May \| Nekajui, Ritz Carlton, Costa Rica**
  
  Forget the Caribbean. The new [Ritz-Carlton resort](https://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/hotels/lirrz-nekajui-peninsula-papagayo-a-ritz-carlton-reserve/overview/ "https://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/hotels/lirrz-nekajui-peninsula-papagayo-a-ritz-carlton-reserve/overview/") in Peninsula Papagayo boasts epic views of Playa Pochote and the Pacific Ocean, four outdoor pools, a private-access beach with natural caves, an ethereal chapel adorned with 650,000 hand-laid mosaic tiles, and [Café Rincón](https://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/hotels/lirrz-nekajui-peninsula-papagayo-a-ritz-carlton-reserve/dining/ "https://www.ritzcarlton.com/en/hotels/lirrz-nekajui-peninsula-papagayo-a-ritz-carlton-reserve/dining/"), a Costa-Rican coffee shop so good it could turn almost anyone into a single-origin aficionado.
  
  And we haven’t even talked about the treetop tents, which make the word “glamping” seem trite. Glamping meets jungle-fantasy is much closer to the mark. Essentially, you’re floating above the rainforest with two bedrooms, a private plunge pool, an outdoor shower and a dedicated personal concierge called a “Manzu,” which translates to _friend_. See what I mean? We’re not in Kansas anymore, Toto.
  
  **Why Book?** Luxury service here is not just a candlelit dinner or a nighttime turndown; At Nekajui, you’ll not just see but _feel_ the ocean waves surge beneath your surfboard, hear the peninsula’s wild biodiversity, taste tropical fruits fallen from the tree, and quite possibly make a new friend.
  
  ![Fishing the Gallatin River with Montage Big Sky](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d7fcf499d7e03b3a470db/Fishing-the-Gallatin-River-with-Montage-Big-Sky/1960x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Fishing the Gallatin River with Montage Big Sky
  
  Jennifer Leigh Parker
  
  **5) June \| Montage Big Sky, Montana, US**
  
  In June, I flew to Bozeman airport with a very specific and long-held intention: to live out my own version of the Norman Maclean novel _A River Runs Through It_ by taking my nephew fly fishing. I’d fallen pretty hard for Montana on a previous trip, when I drove myself clean across the state in a rental Mazda in search of _the last best place_. So, I already knew how Big Sky could make you feel small and insignificant, while granting you the freedom to be big. What I didn’t know was just how seriously Montage would take their higher calling — teaching us to fish on its majestic rivers. They did it with such empathy and grace that the responsibility of passing on the skill of tying one’s own flies to future generations now rests heavy on our shoulders.
  
  It was, in short, a bonding experience. (Read the [full story here](https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/2025/07/25/luxury-fly-fishing-is-a-thing---where-to-cast-in-big-sky-montana/ "https://www.forbes.com/sites/jenniferleighparker/2025/07/25/luxury-fly-fishing-is-a-thing---where-to-cast-in-big-sky-montana/")). When I return, hopefully with even more of my kin, they’ll want to ski the mountain. Hike the trails. Drink the whisky and eat the barbecue. But only the ones who fly fish will be the ones who truly understand it.
  
  **Why Book?** Luxury fly fishing Montage-style, i.e. with a guide who saves you from all manner of caught-on-a-rock, broken line foibles and even serves you lunch on the banks of the Gallatin River is very much a reason to travel.
  
  ![Flute, the rooftop bar inside the Broadwick  ](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d802c0458aaec954d38cd/Flute--the-rooftop-bar-inside-the-Broadwick/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Flute, the rooftop bar inside the Broadwick
  
  The Broadwick Soho
  
  **6) July \| The Broadwick Soho, London**
  
  Think of this [57-room boutique hotel](https://www.broadwicksoho.com/ "https://www.broadwicksoho.com/") as your key to Soho, an irresistibly smutty neighborhood which also manages to attract the upper class with Michelin-starred restaurants and private members' clubs. There’s always a lot going on well into the wee hours, but if you’re not connected, you’ll likely miss the best of it. Under the stewardship of Managing Director Joshua Gardner and owner Noel Hayden, the staff are poised to help you get into the best restaurants, jazz clubs, cocktail bars, art galleries, shows and musicals without you ever having to pick up your phone. That said, you could be forgiven for never leaving your room, a cossetted refuge designed by Martin Brudnizki in characteristic animal-print and velvet settee fashion. (The best room is the Broadwick Suite with its jade green marble bathroom and deep soaking tub, rainfall shower, Ortigia toiletries, free new-release movies and a bronze sculpture elephant that doubles as a mini bar).
  
  **Why Book?**“We kindly ask guests not to use their phones in Flute,” should tell you everything you need to know about the caviar-and-champagne rooftop bar, with wraparound terrace and built-in DJ booth.
  
  ![A produce garden on the grounds of the Newt in Somerset, England](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d80ba7d26a0a7a1f2837a/A-produce-garden-on-the-grounds-of-the-Newt-in-Somerset--England/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  A produce garden on the grounds of the Newt in Somerset, England
  
  Courtesy The Newt
  
  **7) July \| The Newt in Somerset, UK**
  
  More than sleeping in a 17th century Georgian mansion or dining like a modern-day King Arthur, the central question presented at this sprawling 2,800-acre property is: _How will you expand your horizons today?_ Will it be the [Roman Villa](https://thenewtinsomerset.com/plan-your-visit/the-roman-villa "https://thenewtinsomerset.com/plan-your-visit/the-roman-villa") experience, in which you witness life unfold during the Roman rule of Bath, recreated with the help of augmented reality? Will it be in the [Story of Gardening](https://thenewtinsomerset.com/plan-your-visit/story-of-gardening "https://thenewtinsomerset.com/plan-your-visit/story-of-gardening") museum, where you can get your hands dirty and tour exotic gardens, each with their own political significance? Will you get lost in manicured hedge mazes? Or harvest apples in the orchard, press them and drink cider straight from the mill? The options are endless, but whatever you choose, you’ll come away feeling more connected to the land and your (better educated) self.
  
  “I often say we are the new Cotswolds, and that's really important. Whilst we are a luxury hotel, where you get all the refinements of that, it's actually about being in nature. It's about going back to your roots. It's about putting your fingers in the soil and understanding how that all came about and why that's important. We’re fascinated with history and heritage as the custodians of this estate, which dates back to 1687. It’s education, but in a subtle way. We're not teaching people what to do, but we're showing how you can do it,” Andrew Foulkes, CEO of Hospitality at the Newt, told me.
  
  **Why Book?** The word “hotel” doesn’t really capture what Karen Roos and Koos Bekker, owners of South Africa’s Babylonstoren, have created in the Newt, which was awarded Three Michelin Keys in 2024 and held onto that status in 2025. “Extraordinary” is a better word for it.
  
  ![Dinner on the beach at Watergate Bay in Cornwall](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d81163af1d7edd78d9e50/Dinner-on-the-beach-at-Watergate-Bay-in-Cornwall/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Dinner on the beach at Watergate Bay in Cornwall
  
  Watergate Bay
  
  **8) July \| Watergate Bay, Cornwall, UK**
  
  As your resident hotel room guru, I feel obliged to tell you that Watergate’s beach lofts 101 and 102 (there are only seven) have the best views of the Bay and gas fireplaces that give off plenty of heat. When you come in bone-soaked from the beach, having surfed all day in a wetsuit, it feels like a blessing from the gods.
  
  Teetering on the edge of the island’s South West Coast, dramatically framed by the rugged cliffs and wild paths immortalized in _The Salt Path_ — [Watergate Bay](https://watergatebay.co.uk/ "https://watergatebay.co.uk") is arguably the best surf beach in the United Kingdom, attracting surfers from well beyond Britain. Despite the challenges of seasonal staffing and the English weather, the long-standing owners, a family called the Ashworths, managed to turn what was once a collection of sleepy cream tea self-catering flats into a modern Boho-chic destination attracting more young than old.
  
  “Will Ashworth is very much the lifeblood of the Watergate brand. He and his brother, 20 years ago, took it on from his mum and dad and transformed it from what was a traditional bucket and spade holiday hotel into the lifestyle brand you see today. Their vision was: _How do we create a ski resort on a beach?_ said Ben Harper, CEO of Watergate Bay Hotel, SeaSpace & Another Place. “In a ski resort, you get the restaurants, the bars, the ski school, the ice skating rink, the swimming pool, and, of course, the mountain and the après-ski vibe, and everyone's there to ski, but it’s this really cool ecosystem. We’ve put that on the beach.”
  
  **Why Book?** Wavehunters surf school offers excellent group and private lessons. Yoga retreats pop-up here too, as do live music sets. To counter the hippie vibes, there is a rather refined restaurant called [Zacry’s](https://watergatebay.co.uk/food-drink/restaurants/zacrys "https://watergatebay.co.uk/food-drink/restaurants/zacrys") (order the charred lion’s mane mushroom risotto and Cornish new potatoes with seaweed butter, and drink in the sunset).
  
  ![Head chef Timon Wolf at Chateau Raymontpierre](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d817572d05355e5d0bc8d/Head-chef-Timon-Wolf-at-Chateau-Raymontpierre/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Head chef Timon Wolf at Chateau Raymontpierre
  
  Jennifer Leigh Parker
  
  **9) August \| Château de Raymontpierre, Jura, Switzerland**
  
  We’re high above the Val Terbi in the Swiss Jura mountains, hand-picking fennel, onion, garlic, zucchini, carrots, and tomatoes from the gardens at [Château de Raymontpierre](https://chateauderaymontpierre.ch/en/?gad_source=1&gad_campaignid=21123950063&gbraid=0AAAAA9djdYqRT7oFBBHPqlc2890nMgTpE&gclid=Cj0KCQiAgvPKBhCxARIsAOlK_EqjwCXe9CQT-5KvbYHSRjS5PgLJ3cTQUpwxSO9HjXNeWFCMbR2p4QgaAs7OEALw_wcB "https://chateauderaymontpierre.ch/en/?gad_source=1&gad_campaignid=21123950063&gbraid=0AAAAA9djdYqRT7oFBBHPqlc2890nMgTpE&gclid=Cj0KCQiAgvPKBhCxARIsAOlK_EqjwCXe9CQT-5KvbYHSRjS5PgLJ3cTQUpwxSO9HjXNeWFCMbR2p4QgaAs7OEALw_wcB"), sniffing each bulb, _oohing and aahing_ over the bounty. When the sky turns twilight blue, and few stars appear, head chef Timon Wolf turns our mini-harvest into a glorious apéro hour set before the castle’s roaring fireplace, with _Crémant de Jura_ wines and cheeses from their own cows. Out of the carved moon wood windows of this 400-year old castle, gentle meadows and forests stretch as far as the eye can see.
  
  “We take what we have and we use all of it. That’s the goal. When we know how many guests, we have almost no food waste,” declares Wolf, who tries, but fails to hide his youthful ambition behind a thick brown mustache and scruffy beard. Over the course of one day, he teaches us how to dry-age meat, ferment and preserve fruit, and make our own Nocino (a rich chestnut liqueur), which can take 10 months to mature. Low and slow is just how things are done at the Château, which was renovated and opened as a hotel in May 2024 by [The Living Circle](https://www.thelivingcircle.ch/en "https://www.thelivingcircle.ch/en"), the hospitality group pioneering luxury agri-tourism in Switzerland. Three of its properties run their own farms, Raymontpierre included.
  
  **Why Book?** The Château hosts only 28 guests at a time, so it feels very intimate and the daily communal dining easily turns strangers into friends. Go for a culinary masterclass, wedding, or hiking trip; you won’t regret it.
  
  ![Inside the Crillon's Cour D'Honneur courtyard](https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/695d81dc965afbc87d75e9a7/Inside-the-Crillon-s-Cour-D-Honneur-courtyard/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&width=144)
  
  Inside the Crillon's Cour D'Honneur courtyard
  
  Courtesy Hôtel de Crillon
  
  **10) December \| Hôtel de Crillon, Paris, France**
  
  Crowning the entire year is [Hôtel de Crillon](https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon "https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon"), a palace originally commissioned by King Louis XV in 1754. Now, it’s a signature Rosewood hotel with modern amenities like Samsung televisions disguised as ornate antique mirrors, installed into [suites fit for Marie Antoinette](https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon/accommodation/signature-suites/suite-marie-antoinette#carousel-cf58c9605c-item-06c5587b44-tabpanel "https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon/accommodation/signature-suites/suite-marie-antoinette#carousel-cf58c9605c-item-06c5587b44-tabpanel").
  
  Having taken a red-eye flight from Newark the night before, hearing ‘your room is ready’ upon arrival at Place de la Concorde was a welcome relief, and set the tone for an impeccable stay. This is in fact the first hotel in Paris to offer butler service to each of its 124 guest rooms. In the context of Paris-before-Christmas, that decision seems genius. The 15 butlers on staff liaise directly with a team of highly connected _Clefs D’Or_ concierges on the ground floor, and together they can essentially make your Parisian dreams come true. For example, I wanted cocktails at the Crillon’s Bar Les Ambassadeurs, a dinner reservation at Le Bon Georges and tickets to Musée de L’Orangerie to see Claude Monet’s iconic _Water Lillies_. My three wishes were not only granted, they were augmented with a smart suggestion to see the new [Art Deco exhibition](https://madparis.fr/1925-2025-Cent-ans-d-Art-deco "https://madparis.fr/1925-2025-Cent-ans-d-Art-deco") at the nearby Musée des Arts décoratifs, presented by Orient Express. Which will lead, one hopes, to deliciously decadent transcontinental train rides.
  
  Apart from that, butlers write personal welcome notes, surprise guests with things like in-room flowers and dessert from the mind-blowing [Butterfly Patisserie](https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon/dining/butterfly-patisserie "https://www.rosewoodhotels.com/en/hotel-de-crillon/dining/butterfly-patisserie") downstairs, or deliver newspapers every morning, in your preferred language. Want your complimentary breakfast in-room at noon? Done. Need a G7 electric taxi pre-booked, so you can make it to the Opéra in time? _Mais, bien sûr_.
  
  **Why Book?** This, my friends, is as good as it gets. According to managing director Vincent Billiard, the main restaurant L’Ecrin will close in 2026 to make way for a new dining concept. While we wait, the Crillon’s upscale bistro Nonos by Chef Paul Pairet and the Rosewood Spa, with its subterranean swimming pool and saunas will keep everyone prettily pampered.
  
